  "title": "NixOS 22.05 („Quokka“)",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ee62ed696f93aa83",
      "text": "NixOS 22.05 („Quokka“): Gnome 42 und Mesa 22 mit atomaren Updates. [https://www.computerbase.de/2022-05/nixos-22-05-quokka-linux-distribution/ computerbase.de] by [[Sven Bauduin]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e9b28b8f054691dc",
      "text": "The LTS kernel Linux 5.15, which is still supported until October 2023, serves as the basis for NixOS 22.05. It has replaced the system kernel Linux 5.10 from the 2021 version and now also supports the latest hardware from AMD, Intel and Nvidia."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c8d4254df1f162f7",
      "text": "# Standalone Package Manager"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f3ef6e24cb6f2902",
      "text": "NixOS does a few things differently than most conventional Linux distributions, as can be seen in particular in the independent package manager Nix.\n\nNixOS provides more than 60,000 software packages via its in-house Nix Packages Collection Nixpkgs. Fedora and openSUSE have also followed suit.\n\nThis kind of data management deviates from the usual division of the file tree, as it is fixed in the [[Filesystem Hierarchy Standard]] (FHS). NixOS links the directories /bin, /sbin and /usr/sbin to /usr/bin, which means that executable files can only be found in this directory."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5edf0a6030430baf",
      "text": "# Atomic Updates Enable Rollback"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c00f83bad90693d2",
      "text": "Another function of NixOS and its Nix package manager are atomic updates, which make it possible to roll back a complete system update if it is faulty, for example.\n\nLarger changes can be evaluated already in advance, parallel to the current installation in a particularly intended virtual machine of the type QEMU. After a reboot, NixOS offers the user both the new and older system states as startup options."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9f9bdb13d0f963f6",
      "text": "More information can be found in the current [https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/release-notes.html#sec-release-22.05 release notes] and the official announcement of NixOS 22.05.[https://discourse.nixos.org/t/nixos-22-05-released/19404 discourse] "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f9f50b6f89f470bd",
      "text": "> A highlight of the release is [[Nix 2.8]], which brings experimental flakes support for the default installed Nix version, along with tonnes of fixes, features and general improvements, like @pennae’s work to improve performance."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ebfeda4d66538265",
      "text": "* NixOS 22.05 released [https://nixos.org/blog/announcements.html#nixos-22.05 post]\n* Release Notes [https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/release-notes.html#sec-release-22.05 manual]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "85b5e47ffe68513b",
      "text": "> security.acme.defaults has been added to simplify configuring settings for many certificates at once. This also opens up the the option to use DNS-01 validation when using enableACME on web server virtual hosts (e.g. services.nginx.virtualHosts.*.enableACME). "
    },
